<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-09-15T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-09-15T00:00:00-05:00" n="1030" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1030">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 851.731/27</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SWG1" type="to"><hi rend="italic">Sharp</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-09-15">
                                    <hi rend="italic">September 15, 1915</hi>.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>1098. American concerns complain that telegraph companies refuse to
                            inform them whether cablegrams to Italy are stopped or delivered. Please
                            bring urgently attention Foreign Office with request that arrangements
                            be made whereby cable companies will be permitted to notify senders of
                            cablegrams exchanged between United States and Italy regarding delivery
                            or non-delivery of their messages when such information is asked for.
                            Refer to assurances of French Foreign Office conveyed your 487, January
                                23.<note n="1" xml:id="d1030fn1">
                                <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_702">p.
                                702</ref>.</note>
                        </p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="#p_LR1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>